tect tampering\n            let existing_bytes = bincode::encode_to_vec(&*existing.get(), bincode::config::standard()).unwrap_or_default();\n            let new_bytes = bincode::encode_to_vec(&msg, bincode::config::standard()).unwrap_or_default();\n            if existing_bytes != new_bytes {\n                warn!(\"Conflicting envelope for message_id={}: relay divergence detected (node {})\", msg.message_id, self.base_urls[i]);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Pros**: Minimal change, stops silent overwrite, surfaces the problem.\n**Cons**: Still discards one copy — the first isn't necessarily the valid one.\n\n### Option B: Preserve all variants, let the client pick (recommended)\n\nChange the aggregation map to `HashMap<MessageID, Vec<OuterEnvelope>>` and collect all distinct copies. The client layer (decryption) tries each variant and uses the one that successfully decrypts/verifies.\n\n```rust\nlet mut messages_by_id: HashMap<MessageID, Vec<OuterEnvelope>> = HashMap::new();\n\nfor msg in messages {\n    let variants = messages_by_id.entry(msg.message_id).or_default();\n    // Only add if this is a distinct envelope\n    let msg_bytes = bincode::encode_to_vec(&msg, bincode::config::standard()).unwrap_or_default();\n    let is_dup = variants.iter().any(|v| {\n        bincode::encode_to_vec(v, bincode::config::standard()).unwrap_or_default() == msg_bytes\n    });\n    if !is_dup {\n        if !variants.is_empty() {\n            warn!(\"Conflicting envelope for message_id={}: {} variants now\", msg.message_id, variants.len() + 1);\n        }\n        variants.push(msg);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe return type changes from `Vec<OuterEnvelope>` to something that exposes conflicts (e.g., flatten to `Vec<OuterEnvelope>` keeping all variants, or return a richer type).\n\n**Pros**: No valid data is lost; client can try decryption on each variant.\n**Cons**: Requires downstream changes to handle multiple variants per message_id. Larger surface change.\n\n### Option